INTRODUCTION¶

Ford GoBike system data; this data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. The dataset contain 183412 rows and 16 columns.

I will be using this dataset to predict if the individual used to bike to complete the trip or not.

In [ ]:
features = ['start_time', 'end_time']

for feat in features:
    bike[feat] = pd.to_datetime(bike[feat])
    
for feat in features:
    print(bike[feat].dtype)

OBJECT TO CATEGORICAL¶

In [ ]:
cat_dict = {
            'member_gender': ['Male', 'Female', 'Other']
            }

for var in cat_dict:
    cat_type = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, 
                                             categories=cat_dict[var])
bike[var] = bike[var].astype(cat_type)

I convert the gender of the member to categorical to help keep it ordered.

In [ ]:
for var in cat_dict:
    print(bike[var].dtype)

In [ ]:
def hist(data, x, bins):
    plt.hist(data[x], bins=bins)
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {x}', size=15)
    plt.xlabel(x, size=12)

I created a function named hist to make my histograms. The histogram shows a distribution of the numeric features in my dataset.

OBSERVATION¶

This plot shows a clearer view of the values in the feature and from that is a right skewed histogram showing a decrease in the values of the time(seconds) spent riding a bike, having its peak value in an estimated time of 375 seconds. This mean that many of the bikers could ride an estimated time of 375 seconds, this chart also showed that after the estimated 375 seconds the duration of rides started to decrease. This can be due to the fact that few people travelled long distance using the bicycle and might have used other means of transportation.

The _member_birthyear is also an interesting column to check, as later on in the project I will like to know if the age will cause members to or not to complete their trip using bike-sharing system.

Concentrating on the ages with more frequency on the plot, one can see that the peak year in this plot appears to be around 1988, subtracting this value from the maximum tick value this gives 32. This appears to be okay as people in their youth can ride bikes more, there is also a decline later on this represents the younger population of members.

OBSERVATION¶

The chart showed an increasing birth year for the members, which is a decrease in the age of the members using the bike-sharing system and with that, the count frequency increased - younger people use the bike-sharing system the most.

QUESTION:¶

WHICH GENDER HAVE THE HIGHEST MAXIMUM, AVERAGE AND MINIMUMU VALUE FOR THE BIRTH YEAR?

In [ ]:
# function to make boxplot
def box(x, y, data, sym):
    sns.boxplot(x=x, y=y, data=data, sym=sym);

VISUALIZATION¶

In [ ]:
box(x='member_gender', y='member_birth_year', data=bike, sym=None);
plt.title('Distribution of birth year for the member gender');

The chart above shows the descriptive statistics of the values in the _member_birthyear grouped by the _membergender column, the above chart tells that both the male and the female gender both have the maximum value for the year, also it shows that the female gender have the highest average value for year.

Considering outliers in the chart the female gender have the minimum value of year.

In [ ]:
box(x='member_gender', y='member_birth_year', data=bike, sym='')
plt.title('Distribution of birth year for the member gender without outliers');

OBSERVATION¶

Both the male and female gender have the maximum value for the year, the female gender having the highest average mean and with outliers the female gender have the minimum value. With the outliers removed from the plot the male gender have the minimum value of year.

# function to make boxplot with hue
def boxh(x, y, data, hue, sym):
    sns.boxplot(x=x, y=y, data=data, hue=hue, sym=sym);
